  "prompt": "How does specific heat and heat capacity differ?",
  "response": "Let me explain the difference between specific heat and heat capacity:\n\nSpecific Heat:\n- A property of a specific material\n- Amount of heat required to raise the temperature of 1 gram of a substance by 1\u00b0C\n- Measured in J/(g\u00b7\u00b0C) or cal/(g\u00b7\u00b0C)\n- Varies for different materials\n- Depends on the substance's composition and molecular structure\n\nHeat Capacity:\n- A property of a particular object or sample\n- Total amount of heat required to raise the temperature of the entire object by 1\u00b0C\n- Measured in J/\u00b0C\n- Depends on the mass and specific heat of the material\n- Calculated by multiplying specific heat by the object's mass\n\nKey Differences:\n1. Specific heat is per gram, heat capacity is for the entire object\n2. Specific heat is an intrinsic property of a material\n3. Heat capacity changes with object size, specific heat remains constant\n4. Formula: Heat Capacity = Mass \u00d7 Specific Heat\n\nExample:\n- 1 g of water requires 4.18 J to raise its temperature by 1\u00b0C (specific heat)\n- 100 g of water requires 418 J to raise its temperature by 1\u00b0C (heat capacity)",
